Given prism is equilateral so, angel of prism, A $=60^{\circ}$

<br/><br/>On first surface light is passing straight without any deviation, hence angle of refraction $\mathrm{r}_1=0^{\circ}$.
<br/><br/>$$
\begin{aligned}
& r_1+i_2=\mathrm{A} \\\\
& 0+i_2=60^{\circ} \\\\
& \Rightarrow i_2=60^{\circ}
\end{aligned}
$$
<br/><br/>On $2^{\text {nd }}$ surface ray, refracting ray is becoming parallel to the junction of surfaces, so $i_2$ will act as critical angle.

<br/><br/>From snell's law $\mu_1 \sin \theta_1=\mu_2 \sin \theta_2$
<br/><br/>$$
\begin{aligned}
& \Rightarrow \frac{3}{2} \sin i_2=\mu \sin \theta_2 \\\\
& \Rightarrow \mu=\frac{3}{2} \times \frac{\sin 60^{\circ}}{\sin 90^{\circ}}=\frac{3}{2} \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}=\frac{3 \sqrt{3}}{4} \text { or } \frac{\sqrt{27}}{4}
\end{aligned}
$$
